\begin_layout Description
3.
 Consider a monopolist who has 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 customers, of which a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is of type 1, and the remaining proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-p)$
\end_inset

 is of type 2.
 The payoff for a consumer of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i={1,2}$
\end_inset

 from consuming quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 of the good is 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=q[t_{i}-q/2]-R(q)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}>t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R(q)$
\end_inset

 denotes the payment made to buy 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 The consumers’ reservation payoff (or consumer surplus) is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The monopolist wishes to discriminate between customers; would he know the
 customers ‘types’ he would extract the full consumer surplus from them.
 However, he is unable to do so, and manages to price discriminate only
 up to the second degree.
 This means he will offer two contracts destined for each type, with contract
 
\begin_inset Formula $i={1,2}$
\end_inset

 to be chosen by type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}=(q_{i},R(q_{i}))$
\end_inset

.
 The monopolist has a constant marginal cost c and no fixed cost so the
 firm’s type-specific profit is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}=R(q_{i})-cq_{i}$
\end_inset

.
